pullRequest.body:
We show that every nonzero fractional ideal `I` of a Dedekind domain `R` can be factored as a finprod `‚àè_v v^{n_v}` over the maximal ideals of `R`, where the exponents `n_v` are integers. We define `FractionalIdeal.count K v I`  to be `n_v`, and we prove some of its properties.

```suggestion
/-- If `exps` is finitely supported, then `val_v(‚àè_w w^{exps w}) = exps v`. -/
theorem count_finprod (exps : HeightOneSpectrum R ‚Üí ‚Ñ§)
    (h_exps : ‚àÄ·∂† v : HeightOneSpectrum R in Filter.cofinite, exps v = 0) :
    count K v (‚àè·∂† v : HeightOneSpectrum R,
      (v.asIdeal : FractionalIdeal R‚Å∞ K) ^ exps v) = exps v := by
```

```suggestion
/-- For fixed `I`, `val_v(I) = 0` for all but finitely many maximal ideals `v` of `R`. -/
theorem finite_factors {I : FractionalIdeal R‚Å∞ K} :
    ‚àÄ·∂† v : HeightOneSpectrum R in Filter.cofinite, count K v I = 0 := by
  by_cases hI : I = 0
  ¬∑ simp [hI, count_zero]
```

```lean
theorem count_coe (J : Ideal R) (hJ : J ‚â† 0) :
    count K v J = (Associates.mk v.asIdeal).count (Associates.mk J).factors := by
  rw [count_well_defined K (J := J) (a := 1), Ideal.span_singleton_one, sub_eq_self,
    Nat.cast_eq_zero, ‚Üê Ideal.one_eq_top, Associates.mk_one, Associates.factors_one,
    Associates.count_zero v.associates_irreducible]
  ¬∑ simpa only [ne_eq, coeIdeal_eq_zero]
  ¬∑ simp

theorem count_coe_nonneg (J : Ideal R) : 0 ‚â§ count K v J := by
  by_cases hJ : J = 0
  ¬∑ simp [hJ, count_zero]
  ¬∑ simp [count_coe K v J hJ]

theorem count_mono {I J} (hI' : I ‚â† 0) (h : I ‚â§ J) : count K v J ‚â§ count K v I := by
  by_cases hJ : J = 0
  ¬∑ exact (hI' (FractionalIdeal.le_zero_iff.mp (h.trans hJ.le))).elim
  have := FractionalIdeal.mul_le_mul_left h J‚Åª¬π
  rw [inv_mul_cancel hJ, FractionalIdeal.le_one_iff_exists_coeIdeal] at this
  obtain ‚ü®J', hJ'‚ü© := this
  rw [‚Üê mul_inv_cancel_left‚ÇÄ hJ I, ‚Üê hJ', count_mul K v hJ, le_add_iff_nonneg_right]
  ¬∑ exact count_coe_nonneg K v J'
  ¬∑ exact hJ' ‚ñ∏ mul_ne_zero (inv_ne_zero hJ) hI'
```

```suggestion
/-- If `I` is a nonzero fractional ideal, `a ‚àà R`, and `J` is an ideal of `R` such that
`I = a‚Åª¬πJ`, then `J` is nonzero. -/
theorem ideal_factor_ne_zero {I : FractionalIdeal R‚Å∞ K} (hI : I ‚â† 0) {a : R} {J : Ideal R}
    (haJ : I = spanSingleton R‚Å∞ (algebraMap R K a)‚Åª¬π * ‚ÜëJ) : J ‚â† 0 := fun h ‚Ü¶ by
  rw [h, Ideal.zero_eq_bot, coeIdeal_bot, MulZeroClass.mul_zero] at haJ
  exact hI haJ

/-- If `I` is a nonzero fractional ideal, `a ‚àà R`, and `J` is an ideal of `R` such that
`I = a‚Åª¬πJ`, then `a` is nonzero. -/
theorem constant_factor_ne_zero {I : FractionalIdeal R‚Å∞ K} (hI : I ‚â† 0) {a : R} {J : Ideal R}
    (haJ : I = spanSingleton R‚Å∞ (algebraMap R K a)‚Åª¬π * ‚ÜëJ) :
    (Ideal.span {a} : Ideal R) ‚â† 0 := fun h ‚Ü¶ by
  rw [Ideal.zero_eq_bot, Ideal.span_singleton_eq_bot] at h
  rw [h, RingHom.map_zero, inv_zero, spanSingleton_zero, MulZeroClass.zero_mul] at haJ
  exact hI haJ
```

```suggestion

theorem count_finsupp_prod (exps : HeightOneSpectrum R ‚Üí‚ÇÄ ‚Ñ§) :
    count K v (exps.prod (HeightOneSpectrum.asIdeal ¬∑ ^ ¬∑)) = exps v := by
  rw [Finsupp.prod, count_prod]
  ¬∑ simp only [count_zpow, count_maximal, mul_ite, mul_one, mul_zero, Finset.sum_ite_eq',
      exps.mem_support_iff, ne_eq, ite_not, ite_eq_right_iff, @eq_comm ‚Ñ§ 0, imp_self]
  ¬∑ exact fun v hv ‚Ü¶ zpow_ne_zero _ (coeIdeal_ne_zero.mpr v.ne_bot)

/-- If `exps` is finitely supported, then `val_v(‚àè_w w^{exps w}) = exps v`. -/
theorem count_finprod (exps : HeightOneSpectrum R ‚Üí ‚Ñ§)
    (h_exps : ‚àÄ·∂† v in Filter.cofinite, exps v = 0) :
    count K v (‚àè·∂† v : HeightOneSpectrum R,
      (v.asIdeal : FractionalIdeal R‚Å∞ K) ^ exps v) = exps v := by
  convert count_finsupp_prod K v (Finsupp.mk h_exps.toFinset exps (fun _ ‚Ü¶ h_exps.mem_toFinset))
  rw [finprod_eq_finset_prod_of_mulSupport_subset (s := h_exps.toFinset), Finsupp.prod]
  ¬∑ rfl
  ¬∑ rw [Finite.coe_toFinset]
    intro v hv h
    rw [mem_mulSupport, h, zpow_zero] at hv
    exact hv (Eq.refl 1)

```
I was able to split this proof into two, which I think will be useful.
Thanks!
